properties.Name: Harpeth River Park
properties.Description: Harpeth River State Park has much historical and archeological significance; there is an ancient Indian Ceremonial Center, Newsom's Mill ruins, and the old Montgomery Bell Ironworks. There are also plenty of recreational options, such as boating, kayaking and canoeing, fishing, hiking, and picnic tables with grills.

properties.Name: Harpeth Knoll Park
properties.Description: Huge grassy field with playground, and shade structure in the summer.

properties.Name: Bellevue Park
properties.Description: Bellevue Park, known as Red Caboose Park, is perfect for picnicking and family fun. There are picnic tables under gazebos, wide open grassy spaces for casual sport, a fully-fenced in playground, an amphitheater and a paved exercise path (five laps to a mile).

properties.Name: Bells Bend Park
properties.Description: Located in western Davidson County, this park takes its name from a peaceful arc of the Cumberland River known as Bells Bend. This rural preserve is defined by its agricultural history, its bountiful opportunities for viewing wildlife, and a landscape shaped by the river. This 808 acre pastoral park opened to the public in 2007 and supports habitat for plants, migratory birds, and other wildlife. Bells Bend Park offers Nashville residents and visitors access to a unique three-fold experience: cultivating knowledge of the natural world, developing outdoor recreation skills, and understanding cultural impacts upon the land. With a vast history spanning all time periods, this is Nashville's most archaeologically significant park. The outdoor center serves as the trailhead for almost six miles of hiking trails and provides programs for numerous user groups on a wide variety of topics.

properties.Name: Alvin G. Beaman Park
properties.Address: 5911 Old Hickory Blvd. and 4111 A & B Little Marrowbone Rd
properties.Description: Beaman Park provides education and awareness programs, interpretive hikes, trail building workdays, exotic pest plant removal, and native planting programs. Early land use included homesteads, farming, orchards, logging and even moonshining. In the 1970s, a group of doctors called the Blueberry Hill Partners used the land as a hunting preserve. In 1996, the Partners sold their preserve to the Metro Nashville government via a generous gift from Mrs. Sally Beaman in honor of her husband, Alvin G. Beaman, who served on the Park Board from 1955 to 1963 and was a prominent Nashville businessman and civic leader. Beaman Park is the largest single gift of land in the history of the Metro Nashville Parks Department.

properties.Name: Edwin Warner Park
properties.Description: Edwin Warner Park is a great, multi-recreational facility with picnic areas, hiking trails, horse trails, golf courses, athletic fields, and is among the historical community.

properties.Name: H. G. Hill Park
properties.Description: H.G. Hill Park is a small, friendly park with picnic tables; a place where people can unwind. There is also a replica of James Robertson's home.

properties.Name: Percy Warner Park
properties.Description: Percy Warner Park is 2684 acres of forest and field, with an equestrian center, horse trails, hiking, picnic areas, cross country running courses, gold courses, athletic fields, and is historically significant to Nashville, TN.

properties.Name: Charlotte Park
properties.Description: A nice, family oriented park.

properties.Name: Joelton Park
properties.Description: Joelton Park is a multi-recreational park with many baseball diamonds, a soccer field, tennis courts, a playground, and a place for picnicking.

properties.Name: West Park
properties.Description: West Park features an ADA approved Tee-Ball field, basketball court, and a playground.

properties.Name: Paradise Ridge Park
properties.Description: Paradise Ridge Park has a playground and swingset, walking trail.

properties.Name: Parmer Park
properties.Description: Parmer Park is the location of the late Parmer school. Now, there are basketball courts, playground, a baseball diamond, walking paths, and lots of grassy area.

properties.Name: England
properties.Description: Stetch of grass and trees, hugging a creek.

properties.Name: Joseph Brown Mullins Park
properties.Description: Mullins Park is a naturalized area with milkweed and great bird watching. There is a paved walking trail and picnic shelter available.

properties.Name: McCabe Park
properties.Description: McCabe Park has a 27-hole golf course and is located next to the McCabe Community Center. The Richland Creek Greenway runs along the side the park.

properties.Name: Richland Park
properties.Description: Richland park has wide open, grassy fields, tennis courts, and a playground.

properties.Name: Bordeaux-Timothy Drive Park
properties.Description: Bordeaux Timothy Park is a wonderful neighborhood park; there is a playground, basketball court, a baseball field, and a tiny trail loop (just over three times around is a mile).

properties.Name: Bordeaux Garden Park
properties.Description: Bordeaux Gardens Park is a multi-facility area with big, grassy fields and sporting accommodations.

properties.Name: Woodmont Park
properties.Description: Woodmont Park is a wonderful park to bring kids; there is a sandbox, playground, tennis courts, basketball courts, and a walking loop.

properties.Name: R. H. Boyd - Preston Taylor Park
properties.Description: Boyd Park has a playground, picnic tables, and a walking path.

properties.Name: Richard W. Hartman Park
properties.Description: Located next to the Hartman Community Center, with many recreational facilities and a pool.

properties.Name: Elmington Park
properties.Description: Elmington Park is a great hangout park with a big, grassy field where many people throughout the community come and play. There are athletic field, tennis courts a playground.

properties.Name: Hadley Park
properties.Description: Located next to the Hadley Park Library, it has much to offer; a community center, recreational sports fields, fitness center, picnic areas, playground, tennis courts, and a pool.

properties.Name: Ted Rhodes Park
properties.Description: 18 hole golf course, soccer complex, tennis courts

properties.Name: Whites Creek Park
properties.Description: Whites Creek Park has big, grassy fields, including a Cricket Field and baseball fields.

properties.Name: McKissack Park
properties.Description: Small, grassy park with basketball court and playground.

properties.Name: Clinton B. Fisk Park
properties.Description: Fisk Park is beautiful park nestled between 25th Avenue and Burch Street. There are many big trees with paved paths, grassy ball fields, basketball court, a playground, picnic area, and exercise stations.

properties.Name: Centennial Park
properties.Description: The most famous feature of Centennial Park is a replica of the Parthenon. But there are many other attractions like Lake Watauga, historical monuments, a sunken garden, open fields, walking and exercise trails. There are also events and festivals held at the Events Shelter or other locations through the park, as well as programs at the Centennial Art Center and Activity Center. Hidden are volleyball courts, two dog parks, and under the Parthenon lies a museum which many visit each year.

properties.Name: Sally Beaman
properties.Description: Quiet area next to Green Hills Library.

properties.Name: Fannie Mae Dees Park
properties.Description: Also knows as Dragon Park, very suitable for small children and family events. There are many different playgrounds and grassy areas for fun, as well as tennis courts and multiple shaded picnic areas.

properties.Name: Elizabeth Park
properties.Description: Small park with basketball courts, grassy area, and a community center.

properties.Name: Radnor Lake State Natural Area
properties.Description: Radnor Lake State Park is located in Davidson County in the midst of the Overton Hills, south of Metropolitan Nashville in the Oak Hill Community. This natural area provides a variety of scenic spots and a diversity of natural habitats ranging from the lake, to streams and placid sloughs. Wildlife and numerous species of plants are in abundance. It is a place that provides scenic, biological, geological, and passive recreational opportunities not found in other metropolitan areas of Nashville's size.

properties.Name: St. Bernard Park
properties.Description: Small, walk-through park.

properties.Name: Watkins Park
properties.Description: Watkins Park is a lovely, neighborhood park with a spray park element, a playground, tennis courts, and lots of grassy area.

properties.Name: William Edmondson Park
properties.Description: Named after William Edmondson, the famous Nashville sculptor who was the first African American to be able to show at the Museum of Modern Art.

properties.Name: Hope Gardens Park
properties.Description: Hope Gardens Park is a small community park, with a gazebo, playground, and jungle gym.

properties.Name: Owen Bradley Park
properties.Address: 1 Music Square E, at Division St.
properties.Description: Small park with statues.

properties.Name: Morgan Park
properties.Description: Morgan Park is located next to the Morgan Park Recreation Center and serves as a trailhead for Magdeburg Greenway, connecting to the Cumberland River Greenway. There is a fountain dedicated to the historical 'Sulfur Springs' incident and recreational facilities.

properties.Name: Flora Wilson Community Park
properties.Address: On Grand Ave, between 14th Ave S and 15th Ave S
properties.Description: This is a great example of a pocket park created with community input to serve as open space for the neighborhood.

properties.Name: Tony Rose Park
properties.Description: Tony Rose Park has a playground and picnic area with grills.

properties.Name: Sevier Park
properties.Description: Sevier Park is a big, multi-purpose park with large, grassy fields, picnic areas, and also has historical significance.

properties.Name: Bicentennial Capitol Mall State Park
properties.Description: The Bicentennial Capitol Mall State Park is located in the shadow of the State Capitol in downtown Nashville. The 19-acre park is designed to complement the Tennessee Capitol Building, give visitors a taste of Tennessee's history and natural wonders, and to serve as a lasting monument to Tennessee's Bicentennial celebration.

properties.Name: Lock One Park
properties.Description: Lock One Park has historic relics throughout the site; Heaton's Station stood here, one of the original lock buildings, a ferry, and buffalo ford. There is a view of the Cumberland River as well as the city of Nashville.

properties.Name: E. S. Rose Park
properties.Description: Rose Park is located on the historic Edgehill Civil War battleground and provides many recreational facilities; baseball and softball fields, soccer fields, basketball court, a walking track, and a NCAA Division I training facility used by Belmont University.

properties.Name: Church Street Park
properties.Description: A nice park to walk through to unwind and relax, especially for inner-city metro workers on their break.

properties.Name: Reservoir Park
properties.Description: Reservoir Park is where Nashville's reservoir is located and is also historically significant. It is a big park with many recreational facilities.

properties.Name: Dallas H. Neil Park
properties.Description: Very small, grassy park with trees.

properties.Name: Public Square Park
properties.Description: Park located at Nashville City Hall.

properties.Name: Walk of Fame Park
properties.Description: The Music City Walk of Fame Park is located across the street from The Country Music Hall of Fame. It is a pleasant park with a 'Walk of Fame' dedicated to Nashville favorites, and it is also a great place for hosting outdoor events and festivals.

properties.Name: Commerce Center Park
properties.Description: A nice park to walk through to unwind and relax, especially for inner-city metro workers on their break. There is a sculpture and sign that explains the history of the area and spotlights the disarmed cannonballs found when excavating for Commerce Center.

properties.Name: Riverfront Park
properties.Description: Riverfront Park runs along 1st Avenue Downtown and hosts Ascend Amphitheater, a dog run, art work and the Fort NAshborough replica

properties.Name: Fort Negley
properties.Description: Original remains of Fort Negley stand at this location, reminding  of the Union Army's successful capture of  Nashville, TN, in 1862 The city was  amajor supply depot and staging area in the western theater.

properties.Name: Parkwood Park
properties.Description: Located next to the Parkwood Recreation Center, there are many recreational opportunities.

properties.Name: Willow Creek Park
properties.Description: A small, grassy area with a playground.

properties.Name: Cumberland Park
properties.Description: Cumberland Park is a play space for children and families and a location for events. There is a stone climbing wall, spray park, bouncing pad, a maze, see-saws, and an outdoor amphitheatre for events.

properties.Name: McFerrin Park
properties.Description: McFerrin Park is located next to the Community Center with tennis courts, basketball courts, baseball field, a playground, swings, and grassy areas.

properties.Name: Dudley Park
properties.Description: I small park with a swing set, grassy field, and a looped path.

properties.Name: Fredrick Douglass Park
properties.Description: Douglas Park has a baseball field as well as plenty of grassy fields.

properties.Name: East Park
properties.Description: East Park has a great community center, playground, swings, and baseball diamonds. It is nestled in historic east Nashville with Victorian-style homes lacing the park boundaries. There are many events that take place within the park.

properties.Name: Cleveland Park
properties.Description: Cleveland Park is a wonderful neighborhood park, with a picnic area, walking paths, a playground, and sporting areas like tennis courts, basketball courts, a volleyball court, baseball fields, and a pool that is open seasonally.

properties.Name: Tom Joy Park
properties.Description: Small park with playground and big, grassy field.

properties.Name: Mildred Shute Minipark
properties.Description: Small community park with a playground.

properties.Name: J. C. Napier Park
properties.Description: J.C. Napier Park is located at the Napier Recreation Center which has an indoor pool. There is a playground and a small, grassy field.

properties.Name: Granbery Park
properties.Description: Granbery Park has playground equipment for the kids and workout equipment for the adults. There is a picnic area, tennis courts, and a baseball field. Check out the beautiful trees!

properties.Name: Oakwood Park
properties.Description: Small community park with a playground, outdoor basketball courts, amphitheater and trail loop

properties.Name: Cedar Hill
properties.Description: Cedar Hill Park offers peaceful areas to escape the urban noise, as well active areas such as baseball fields, a duck pond, playground, paths, and covered pavilions with picnic tables. There is also an 18 hole disc golf course located within the park.

properties.Name: Shelby Walk Park
properties.Description: Small, walk-through park with picnic area.

properties.Name: Turner School Park
properties.Description: Turner School Park is great for a small park; there is a jungle gym, kickball field, picnic areas with grills, and a walking path.

properties.Name: William Coleman Park

properties.Name: Bass Park

properties.Name: Grassmere / Nashville Zoo
properties.Description: The Nashville Zoo provides education programs, annual saffari, historic homes, and jungle gyms.

properties.Name: William Whitfield Park
properties.Description: Park with baseball fields and a playground.

properties.Name: Eastland Park
properties.Description: Eastland Park is a wonderful neighborhood park oriented to families; playground, a grassy field, and picnic area.

properties.Name: Lockeland Springs Park

properties.Name: Shelby Park
properties.Description: Shelby Park is a large, multi-use park along the Cumberland River. It features Sevier Lake, boating, a fenced dog park, an event field, athletic fields and courts, golf courses, and free educational programs.

properties.Name: Wentworth-Caldwell Park
properties.Description: Huge, open grassy field. Perfect for soccer.

properties.Name: South Inglewood Park
properties.Description: South Inglewood Park is a great multi-use park with a Community Center.

properties.Name: Isaac Litton School Park
properties.Description: Small, school park with volleyball court, tennis courts, playground and picnic area.

properties.Name: Paragon Mills Park
properties.Description: Paragon Mills Park has baseball fields, basketball courts, a playground, and grassy areas.

properties.Name: Providence Park
properties.Description: Small, community park with playground and walkways connecting the neighborhood.

properties.Name: William A. Pitts Park
properties.Description: Forested park with a baseball field, playground and basketball court.

properties.Name: Shelby Bottoms Park
properties.Description: The 960-acre Shelby Bottoms Greenway and Nature Park is located in East Nashville adjacent to Shelby Park and is one of five Natural Area Parks within Metro Parks. With approximately three miles of Cumberland River frontage, this area features bottomland hardwood forests, open fields, wetlands, and streams, providing excellent habitat for birds, amphibians, deer and more.

properties.Name: Lock Two Park
properties.Description: Lock Two Park is a charming and lovely family park. It is nestled in a bend of the Cumberland River, and still standing is one of Nashville's original lockkeeper residences. There is a boat ramp and a boat-themed playground.

properties.Name: Madison Park
properties.Description: Madison Park is located next to the Madison Community Center, with pavilion, playgrounds, multi-recreational fields and courts.

properties.Name: Seven Oaks Park
properties.Description: Seven Oaks Park is a huge recreational facility with lots of grassy fields, athletic fields, a disc golf course, picnic areas, and a playground.

properties.Name: Two Rivers Park
properties.Description: Two Rivers Park is a huge park featuring many activities; Wave Country water park, golf course, disc golf course, Greenhouse, picnicking and playgrounds, as well as historical attributes such as the Two Rivers Mansion.

properties.Name: Ezell Road Park
properties.Description: Ezell Road Park is adjacent to the Mill Creek Greenway and has a ton of area, perfect for soccer.

properties.Name: Antioch Park
properties.Description: Antioch Park is home of the Antioch Community Center and the Mill Creek Greenway.

properties.Name: Heartland Park
properties.Description: Heartland Park is perfect for soccer players. Stones River Greenway runs along side the park.

properties.Name: E. N. Peeler Park
properties.Description: Peeler Park is giant and friendly to Bicyclists, horseback riders, remote-control plane enthusiasts, and boating. There are signs with the historical significance about the land. It is more of a greenway type than recreational park.

properties.Name: Una Recreation Park
properties.Description: Una Park is comprised of big, grassy fields, primarily used for football.

properties.Name: Cecil Rhea Crawford Park
properties.Description: At Cecil Rhea Crawford park, the main attraction is the old Cane Ridge School House which is now a Community center.

properties.Name: Lakewood Park
properties.Description: Two baseball field park.

properties.Name: Stone Hall Park
properties.Description: Stone Hall was built in 1918 by Nashville architect George Waller for the Cantrell family, it is significance in Colonial Revival architecture.

properties.Name: Hamilton Creek Park
properties.Description: Hamilton Creek Mountain Bike Park is the only mountain biking park within Davidson County, Nashville, TN. It also offers many other attractions such as a Sailboat Marina with boat launch ramps and a playground.

properties.Name: Cane Ridge Park
properties.Description: Cane Ridge Park is huge and accommodating for sports, including soccer, baseball, and basketball. This park also offers an Airstrip for model airplanes.

properties.Name: Hermitage Park
properties.Description: Hermitage Park is located at the Hermitage Recreation Center. It includes a library, a playground, lots of grassy areas, and a cool sundial sculpture.

properties.Name: Long Hunter State Park
properties.Description: Long Hunter State Park is situated along the shore of J. Percy Priest Lake. It consists of four units: Couchville, Baker's Grove, Bryant Grove and Sellars Farm. Picnicking, swimming, hiking, backpacking, boating, fishing, nature photography and wildlife observation are among the activities available to park visitors. Planned activities include interpretive and recreation programs for the general public and environmental education programs for school and other interested groups.

properties.Name: Couchville Cedar Glade State Natural Area
properties.Description: Couchville Cedar Glade is a 122-acre natural area in Davidson and Wilson Counties and is contiguous with the east boundary of Long Hunter State Park. Couchville supports one of the largest known and best quality populations of the federally endangered Tennessee coneflower (Echinacea tennesseensis). Couchville also provides one of the finest examples of a glade-barrens complex and protects many rare plant species.
properties.CommonName: Couchville Cedar Glade State Natural Area

properties.Name: Monroe Street Playground
properties.Description: Monroe is a small park in a residential community

properties.Name: City Cemetery
properties.Description: The City Cemetery is the oldest continuously operated public cemetery in Nashville.

properties.Name: Metro Soccer Complex
properties.Description: Soccer complex with 7 unlit fields

properties.Name: Mount View Glade State Natural Area
properties.Description: Mount View Glade is a nine-acre natural area in Davidson County that was purchased by The Nature Conservancy in 1990 and later transferred to the State of Tennessee. It is located in suburban Nashville and is surrounded by subdivisions. This small natural area is fenced and gated with a small pull off area for limited public access. The natural area was acquired and then designated to protect one of five populations of the federally endangered Tennessee coneflower (Echinacea tennesseensis). Mt. View has been an area that has provided research opportunities for the recovery and protection of Tennessee coneflower through funding provided by the US Fish and Wildlife Service.
properties.CommonName: Mount View Glade State Natural Area

properties.Description: Cemetery

properties.Description: Brookmeade Park is located at Kelly's Point Battlefield, the site of a battle in the Civil War. It leads to a bike-friendly greenway and a small, simple overlook of the river. The trail here, like other trails, will eventually be connected to other parts of the Cumberland River Greenway.
